{
  "analysis": "The current /app/mystery.c is a guessed raytracer and is verified wrong: image md5 a36bc6586fa014f9e174053d77d88f53 vs required e866fa2c851f4a9da736b4ed3ba3912e. The candidate outputs near-black first pixels (16 16 16) while the original starts with sky (159 197 255). We have /tmp/main_dis.txt and extracted constants (2.6666667, 1.33333337, sky parameters 0.2/0.9, scene constants at 0x485a58/0x485ad0), but no implementation has matched. The next concrete step is to inspect helper functions and the exact main inner loop to reconstruct the algorithm rather than guessing. We should dump vector_normalize and allocate_image, and print main lines 81-200 in manageable chunks. We must avoid additional guessed implementations until they can be verified byte-for-byte against /tmp/original.ppm.",
  "plan": "Dump the helper functions vector_normalize (0x4020a0) and allocate_image (0x402de0), and print main disassembly lines 81-200 in small sections. This will reveal the exact camera basis, ray generation, and color logic used by the original binary, enabling a correct implementation.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "cd /app; echo '--- nm around main/helpers ---'; nm -C /app/mystery | grep -E ' [tT] ' | awk '$1>=\"0000000000401740\" && $1<=\"0000000000403100\" {print}' | head -80\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo '--- vector_normalize ---'; objdump -d -Mintel /app/mystery --start-address=0x4020a0 --stop-address=0x402180 | sed -n '1,120p'\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo '--- allocate_image ---'; objdump -d -Mintel /app/mystery --start-address=0x402de0 --stop-address=0x402f80 | sed -n '1,120p'\n",
      "duration": 1.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo '--- main 81-120 numbered ---'; grep -n \"\" /tmp/main_dis.txt | sed -n '81,120p'\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo '--- main 121-160 numbered ---'; grep -n \"\" /tmp/main_dis.txt | sed -n '121,160p'\n",
      "duration": 0.1
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "echo '--- main 161-200 numbered ---'; grep -n \"\" /tmp/main_dis.txt | sed -n '161,200p'\n",
